You can use a variable to set the `commandToExecute` like this:

    &quot;executeCommand&quot;: &quot;[concat(&#39;sh samplebash.sh&#39;, &#39; &#39;, parameters(&#39;azUsername&#39;), &#39; &#39;, parameters(&#39;azPassword&#39;))]&quot;

Then you can set the extension like this:

    &quot;commandToExecute&quot;: &quot;[variables(&#39;executeCommand&#39;)]&quot;

Or you can set the extension directly like this:

    &quot;commandToExecute&quot;: &quot;[concat(&#39;sh samplebash.sh&#39;, &#39; &#39;, parameters(&#39;azUsername&#39;), &#39; &#39;, parameters(&#39;azPassword&#39;))]&quot;

And in the script, you should do some changes, there are two ways.

**First:**

    #!/bin/bash
    
    echo &quot;azUsername:$1&quot;
    echo &quot;azPassword:$2&quot;

**Second:**

    #!/bin/bash
    
    azUsername=$1
    azPassword=$2
    echo $azUsername
    echo $azPassword

By the way, I think when you use the `#!/bin/bash` in the script, then you&#39;d better execute the script with the command `bash script.sh`. In some Linux distribution, `sh` is not the same command as `bash`.

